<Layout>
  <div class="container my-4">
    <div class="row justify-content-center">
      <div class="col-sm-12 col-md-10">
        <a href="/java-programming/" class="btn btn-sm btn-outline-light mb-3">
          <i class="si-arrow-left"></i> Back
        </a>

        <h1>Activity 5.14 — String Methods</h1>
        <Divider variant="8" classes="mb-4" />

        <h2>Introduction</h2>

        <Presentation>
          <section>
            <h3>Activity 4-9</h3>
            <h4 class="text-skynest-theme">String Methods</h4>
          </section>

          <section>
            <h4>Strings are objects</h4>
            <ul>
              <li><code>String</code> is a class.</li>
              <li>A String variable stores a String object.</li>
              <li>Objects have methods you can call with dot notation.</li>
            </ul>
            <Code code={SlideA} lang="java" class="text-start" />
          </section>

          <section>
            <h4>One easy confusion</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Arrays use <code>length</code></li>
              <li>Strings use <code>length()</code></li>
            </ul>
            <Code code={SlideB} lang="java" class="text-start" />
          </section>

          <section>
            <h4><code>substring</code></h4>
            <ul>
              <li><code>substring(start, end)</code> includes the start index.</li>
              <li>It does <strong>not</strong> include the end index.</li>
              <li><code>substring(start)</code> goes from start to the end of the string.</li>
            </ul>
            <Code code={SlideC} lang="java" class="text-start" />
          </section>

          <section>
            <h4><code>indexOf</code></h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Finds the first position of a character or substring.</li>
              <li>If nothing is found, it returns <code>-1</code>.</li>
            </ul>
            <Code code={SlideD} lang="java" class="text-start" />
          </section>

          <section>
            <h4>Comparing Strings</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Use <code>equals</code> to test if two strings have the same text.</li>
              <li>Do <strong>not</strong> use <code>==</code> for String comparison on the AP exam.</li>
            </ul>
            <Code code={SlideE} lang="java" class="text-start" />
          </section>

          <section>
            <h4><code>compareTo</code></h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Used for alphabetical comparison.</li>
              <li>Negative means “comes before.”</li>
              <li>Positive means “comes after.”</li>
              <li>Zero means the strings are equal.</li>
            </ul>
            <Code code={SlideF} lang="java" class="text-start" />
          </section>

          <section>
            <h4>Strings are immutable</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>String methods do not change the original String.</li>
              <li>They return a new String instead.</li>
              <li>If you want the change, assign the result to a variable.</li>
            </ul>
            <Code code={SlideG} lang="java" class="text-start" />
          </section>

          <section>
            <h4>Today's goals</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Use common AP String methods correctly.</li>
              <li>Extract pieces of text with <code>substring</code>.</li>
              <li>Search for text with <code>indexOf</code>.</li>
              <li>Compare Strings with <code>equals</code> and <code>compareTo</code>.</li>
            </ul>
          </section>
        </Presentation>

        <section id="objectives">
          <h3>Objectives</h3>
          <ul>
            <ListItem>Use common String methods including <code>length()</code>, <code>substring()</code>, and <code>indexOf()</code>.</ListItem>
            <ListItem>Compare strings using <code>equals()</code> and <code>compareTo()</code>.</ListItem>
            <ListItem>Explain why Strings are immutable.</ListItem>
            <ListItem>Solve small text-processing problems using String methods.</ListItem>
          </ul>
        </section>

        <Divider variant="8" classes="mb-4" />

        <section id="activity-tasks">
          <h2>Activity Tasks</h2>
          <ul>
            <ListItem variant="2">Create a new project named <span class="text-skynest-theme">Activity4-9-StringMethods</span>.</ListItem>
            <ListItem variant="2">Complete Tasks 1-5.</ListItem>
            <ListItem variant="2">Use the figures as references while you work.</ListItem>
          </ul>

